JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).

  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.

  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Bläsing","email":"2733b4844ad39354bd21fd2bca55a8804e19a60d@doppel-helix.eu"},"message":"[NETBEANS-5142] LSP Client creates excessive processes (#2589)

The caching of the LSP client that is rooted in project2MimeType2Server
does not work. In the WeakHashMap the keys are help by weak references
and the key is invalidated, once it is GCed. The URIs that are used
as keys become immediately eligible for GC and thus the cache is not
used at all.

To fix this, use a regular HashMap with WeakReference values.

The LSP Clients themselves are either strongly referenced from other
components or can be collected. To not create excessive start/stops of
servers, an additional strong reference is retained for a certain time
after the last bind request was issued. Only after the timeout has
occured, that extra reference is released and the bindings could become
eligible for GC.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Akshay-Gupta-Oracle/netbeans/commits/ebde2a5904506dc10a035e8e4ef9adbc80889b02"},{"sha":"b6104f59cea7350169f9d0737350bc71225b1e6c","author":{"name":"Dusan Balek","email":"93d74d1cc9df89834360f8b313cef058ebced495@oracle.com"},"message":"Existing CodeGenerators exposed as CodeActions via LSP. [{"sha":"fde93bf32a2d24772f63bc99680f0973399cf1eb","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add hello_world example to the output tree.

This is a first-pass implementation of what exporting the example code
would look like. In particular:
 * We will only export the x86 versions of the examples.
 * Any target specific specializations or additional sources will be
   handled outside of the TFLM codebase (i.e. in the target's example
   repository).

Also,

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362098871
Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

[{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"}]

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

This isn't incredibly important, but Kitchen-Terraform is written in and requires tests to be written in Ruby.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f172585eaa23b9edc40c5b73b066654e1bae7120"},{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

This isn't incredibly important, but Kitchen-Terraform is written in and requires tests to be written in Ruby.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f172585eaa23b9edc40c5b73b066654e1bae7120"},{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

Fix #1273

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly@koyeb.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tharun208/kuma/commits/004a4e14350941b158b04c12fb29c2f1a210856f"},{"sha":"de170f1b889d0562321bced10097edfcbba147ce","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"6d801fb2355a07c9e004ea4635b4ce3edfe405d7@koyeb.com"},"message":"fix(dns) allow resolution of service names with "." (#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

* Rename "name"->"filepath" field on Webpack module references

This field name will get confused with the imported name or the module id.

* Switch back to transformSource instead of getSource

getSource would be more efficient in the cases where we don't need to read
the original file but we'll need to most of the time.

Even then, we can't return a JS file if we're trying to support non-JS
loader because it'll end up being transformed.

Similarly, we'll need to parse the file and we can't parse it before it's
transformed. So we need to chain with other loaders that know how.

* Add acorn dependency

This should be the version used by Webpack since we have a dependency on
Webpack anyway.

* Parse exported names of ESM modules

We need to statically resolve the names that a client component will
export so that we can export a module reference for each of the names.

For export * from, this gets tricky because we need to also load the
source of the next file to parse that. We don't know exactly how the
client is built so we guess it's somewhat default.

* Handle imported names one level deep in CommonJS using a Proxy

We use a proxy to see what property the server access and that will tell
us which property we'll want to import on the client.

* Add export name to module reference and Webpack map

To support named exports each name needs to be encoded as a separate
reference. It's possible with module splitting that different exports end
up in different chunks.

It's also possible that the export is renamed as part of minification.
So the map also includes a map from the original to the bundled name.

* Special case plain CJS requires and conditional imports using __esModule

This models if the server tries to import .default or a plain require.
We should replicate the same thing on the client when we load that
module reference.

* Dedupe acorn-related deps

Co-authored-by: Mateusz Burzyński <mateuszburzynski@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sanfengliao/react/commits/3f73dcee374732a331b7e72c88ff6dd3b7116a42"},{"sha":"5711811da17c62de7ba6c911dbc7f20f16bfc980","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"Reconcile element types of lazy component yielding the same type (#20357)

* Reconcile element types of lazy component yielding the same type

* Add some legacy mode and suspense boundary flushing tests

* Fix infinite loop in legacy mode

In legacy mode we typically commit the suspending fiber and then rerender
the nearest boundary to render the fallback in a separate commit.

We can't do that when the boundary itself suspends because when we try to
do the second pass, it'll suspend again and infinite loop.

Interestingly the legacy semantics are not needed in this case because
they exist to let an existing partial render fully commit its partial state.

In this case there's no partial state, so we can just render the fallback
immediately instead.

* Check fast refresh compatibility first

resolveLazy can suspend and if it does, it can resuspend. Fast refresh
assumes that we don't resuspend. Instead it relies on updating the inner
component later.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

[{"sha":"0998d1ed771cd751c8f2516ba3c2146224879bf3","author":{"name":"Masayuki Morita","email":"eeb27ba991126edcc4750d96da45cd275e56eb2e@gmail.com"},"message":"command/init: Add a new flag `-lockfile=readonly` (#27630)

Fixes #27506

Add a new flag `-lockfile=readonly` to `terraform init`.
It would be useful to allow us to suppress dependency lockfile changes
explicitly.

The type of the `-lockfile` flag is string rather than bool, leaving
room for future extensions to other behavior variants.

The readonly mode suppresses lockfile changes, but should verify
checksums against the information already recorded. It should conflict
with the `-upgrade` flag.

Note: In the original use-case described in #27506, I would like to
suppress adding zh hashes, but a test code here suppresses adding h1
hashes because it's easy for testing.

Co-authored-by: Alisdair McDiarmid <alisdair@users.noreply.github.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0998d1ed771cd751c8f2516ba3c2146224879bf3"},{"sha":"68a4210dac29d59bcedb129624f05b4da4472020","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #28026 from hashicorp/alisdair/backport-27630-v0.15

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

[{"sha":"c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add missing includes to ensure that we export all the required headers.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

- to reduce binaries size of FFmpeg Windows wrapper
- MinGW linker doesn't support -ffunction-sections (used for FFmpeg Windows wrapper)
- move code to improve locality with its used dependencies
- move UMat::dot() to matmul.dispatch.cpp (Mat::dot() is already there)
- move UMat::inv() to lapack.cpp
- move UMat::mul() to arithm.cpp
- move UMat:eye() to matrix_operations.cpp (near setIdentity() implementation)
- move normalize(): convert_scale.cpp => norm.cpp
- move convertAndUnrollScalar(): arithm.cpp => copy.cpp
- move scalarToRawData(): array.cpp => copy.cpp
- move transpose(): matrix_operations.cpp => matrix_transform.cpp
- move flip(), rotate(): copy.cpp => matrix_transform.cpp (rotate90 uses flip and transpose)
- add 'OPENCV_CORE_EXCLUDE_C_API' CMake variable to exclude compilation of C-API functions from the core module
- matrix_wrap.cpp: add compile-time checks for CUDA/OpenGL calls
- the steps above allow to reduce FFmpeg wrapper size for ~1.5Mb (initial size of OpenCV part is about 3Mb)

backport is done to improve merge experience (less conflicts)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

[{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

This fixes an issue where if a build requests an image that already
exists in Docker's image store but does not match the specified build
platform, instead of building using the wrong platform go ahead and
check the remote for the correct platform.

Steps to reproduce issue:

```terminal
$ docker pull --platform=amd64 debian:buster
<output supressed>
$ cat Dockerfile
FROM debian:buster
RUN echo hello
$ docker build --platform=armhf -< Dockerfile
<output supressed>
```

Without this fix, the build invokcation will build using the amd64 image
since it is already tagged locally, but this is clearly not what we
want.

With the fix the local image is not used and instead we pull the correct
image.

This code was originally written for v1.10 migration where it signified that layers
were recomputed from pre 1.8 layout and could possibly change the tarball checksums.

It's now being repurposed in the BuildKit adapter but there it doesn't have any
warn condition as all data generated by builder is new anyway.

Currently, debug log entries as the one below may appear in the daemon logs:

   [2019-10-02T10:00:06.690674253Z] could not get checksum for "x128nsj79yzfx4j5h6em2w2on" with tar-split: "no tar-split file"

This patch removes the debug log, as it may confuse users ("we couldn't validate
what we downloaded, but we're gonna run it anyway?")

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.
