Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: I071d64b93ff28be3c6e8a152f0bb52672da8c9c9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/0bed64d710ee0f87c1b3bb10f48b1ab0f5ed797b"},{"sha":"ea4cf3c25175b09727a52e37b044dd92b03dc3b0","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Report an error on consumer restarts in round robin reads.

In round robin read mode, we store the latest round of data in case a network error causes a consumer to need to retry. Before this CL, we would provide the data for the latest round N for any round request R such that R <= N. If a consumer was restarted with the same job name, the first N elements it gets from a worker would be identical. After this CL, we will report an error instead.

This CL also fixes an IteratorContext lifetime issue in data_service_dataset_ops that was causing the added test to fail.

Changes ownership of PjRtBuffers in PyBuffer to shared ownership.

JAX's C++ jit keeps certain metadata on PyBuffer objects, but we need to be able to create copies of buffers with different metadata without copying the buffers. The canonical example of this is the sticky device property of JAX arrays. Currently JAX does this by wrapping a Python _DeviceArray object around the C++ buffer object, but we would like to remove the Python wrapper.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362152148
Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

In profiles from repositry updater runs a huge CPU load originating 
from SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl was found. In parallel excessive runtimes
for project scanning were observed.

Comparing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl and SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation
the latter has an aggressive caching system, which results in much less
cpu usage. Just removing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl is not a solution, as
it is used to override the default project detection from
SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation.

Explanation from Jaroslav Tulach:

[...] Historically the Graal project provided mx netbeansinit support
which generates 8.2 Ant nbproject/project.xml projects based on content
of suite/mx.suite/suite.py. They were usually located in
suite/src/*/nbproject directories.

To fix this, the idea is, not only to use the current MX project
detection (it requires a folder `mx.proj` to be found in the project
folder `proj`), but also look two level ups from the current directory.
If that directory is recognised as a MX project, that project will
be returned as the project for the requested directory.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/singh-akhilesh/netbeans/commits/460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892"},{"sha":"2ccf4467602226a4becf95c41583d0ff82fd3423","author":{"name":"Svata Dedic","email":"023eb79affb3895450c68d8beb536005684ec349@oracle.com"},"message":"Trust priming build, as the user already saw the warning.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/singh-akhilesh/netbeans/commits/2ccf4467602226a4becf95c41583d0ff82fd3423"},{"sha":"a04c16cb0ff0afe4ee565d360370fa5b4f169578","author":{"name":"Neil C Smith","email":"e98d4a33b51c12d4a3a2e22317e3af9557a6599a@apache.org"},"message":"Snapshot of APIs as of 12.3.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/singh-akhilesh/netbeans/commits/a04c16cb0ff0afe4ee565d360370fa5b4f169578"},{"sha":"085718c35c16a53b667d4a4d0a75f46cb046d9c2","author":{"name":"Přemek Vyhnal","email":"ba4dd204299ff3080cf3373035325ee58babf0c5@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"fix travis link in readme","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/singh-akhilesh/netbeans/commits/085718c35c16a53b667d4a4d0a75f46cb046d9c2"},{"sha":"2691d4aed348ce2dc059131496d3c9fc251f8626","author":{"name":"Svatopluk Dedic","email":"023eb79affb3895450c68d8beb536005684ec349@oracle.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #2787 from sdedic/gradle/trustPrimingBuild

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

[{"sha":"c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add missing includes to ensure that we export all the required headers.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /
sources that are exported by the TFLM project generation scripts.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649"},{"sha":"e2a159ad34a6a775c4a857e56fd5efc26084c086","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into project_generation_v2-3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/e2a159ad34a6a775c4a857e56fd5efc26084c086"},{"sha":"8bf557c642fdc7e3f8f7e7a8679746c8e183039b","author":{"name":"Hanhan Wang","email":"17db91a825a40156b2c20ef2022824cbafd12aac@google.com"},"message":"Add support for lowering NHWC pooling mhlo.reduce_window to Linalg on tensors.

npm will sometimes fail if you try to concurrently publish two different
versions of the same package, even if they use different dist tags.

So instead of publishing to the Next and Experimental channels

When running the publish workflow, either via the command line or
via the daily cron job, we should use a constant SHA instead of
whatever happens to be at the head of the main branch at the time the
workflow is run.

The difference is subtle: currently, the SHA is read at runtime,
each time the workflow is run. With this change, the SHA is read right
before the workflow is created and passed in as a constant parameter.

In practical terms, this means if a workflow is re-run via the CircleCI
web UI, it will always re-run using the same commit SHA as the original
workflow, instead of fetching the latest SHA from GitHub, which may
have changed.

Also avoids a race condition where the head SHA changes in between the
Next publish job and the Experimental publish job.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/renatoalencar/react/commits/9e8f3c89555e4a2a1877c27d710b4d4c1e069014"},{"sha":"e2fd460cca3b11fa0f5505f324043a9b2d9db894","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bailout in sync task if work is not sync (#20813)

Because we don't cancel synchronous tasks, sometimes more than one
synchronous task ends up being scheduled. This is an artifact of the
fact that we have two different lanes that schedule sync tasks: discrete
and sync. So what can happen is that a discrete update gets scheduled,
then a sync update right after that. Because sync is encoded as higher
priority than discrete, we schedule a second sync task. And since we
don't cancel the first one, there are now two separate sync tasks.

As a next step, what we should do is merge InputDiscreteLane with
SyncLane, then (I believe) this extra bailout wouldn't be necessary,
because there's nothing higher priority than sync that would cause us to
cancel it. * The exported '<React.StrictMode>' tag remains the same and opts legacy subtrees into strict mode level one ('mode == StrictModeL1'). This mode enables DEV-only double rendering, double component lifecycles, string ref warnings, legacy context warnings, etc. The primary purpose of this mode is to help detected render phase side effects. No new behavior. Roots created with experimental 'createRoot' and 'createBlockingRoot' APIs will also (for now) continue to default to strict mode level 1.

In a subsequent commit I will add support for a 'level' attribute on the '<React.StrictMode>' tag (as well as a new option supported by ). This will be the way to opt into strict mode level 2 ('mode == StrictModeL2'). This mode will enable DEV-only double invoking of effects on initial mount. This will simulate future Offscreen API semantics for trees being mounted, then hidden, and then shown again. The primary purpose of this mode is to enable applications to prepare for compatibility with the new Offscreen API (more information to follow shortly).

For now, this commit changes no public facing behavior. The only mechanism for opting into strict mode level 2 is the pre-existing 'enableDoubleInvokingEffects' feature flag (only enabled within Facebook for now).

* Renamed strict mode constants

StrictModeL1 -> StrictLegacyMode and StrictModeL2 -> StrictEffectsMode

* Renamed tests

* Split strict effects mode into two flags

One flag ('enableStrictEffects') enables strict mode level 2. It is similar to 'debugRenderPhaseSideEffectsForStrictMode' which enables srtict mode level 1.

The second flag ('createRootStrictEffectsByDefault') controls the default strict mode level for 'createRoot' trees. For now, all 'createRoot' trees remain level 1 by default. We will experiment with level 2 within Facebook.

This is a prerequisite for adding a configurable option to 'createRoot' that enables choosing a different StrictMode level than the default.

* Add StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop and createRoot 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option

New StrictMode 'unstable_level' prop allows specifying which level of strict mode to use. If no level attribute is specified, StrictLegacyMode will be used to maintain backwards compatibility. Otherwise the following is true:
* Level 0 does nothing
* Level 1 selects StrictLegacyMode
* Level 2 selects StrictEffectsMode (which includes StrictLegacyMode)

Levels can be increased with nesting (0 -> 1 -> 2) but not decreased.

This commit also adds a new 'unstable_strictModeLevel' option to the createRoot and createBatchedRoot APIs. This option can be used to override default behavior to increase or decrease the StrictMode level of the root.

* If a nested StrictMode tag attempts to explicitly decrease the level
* If a level attribute changes in an update","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/renatoalencar/react/commits/9209c30ff98528cfbbe9df0774fda0b117975a25"},{"sha":"8336f19aa80c6646d6969fa61e34420776d884be","author":{"name":"Rubén Norte","email":"4189b3e49b7b603e152f4113b2d535bfb643d616@gmail.com"},"message":"Update React Native types (#20883)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/renatoalencar/react/commits/8336f19aa80c6646d6969fa61e34420776d884be"},{"sha":"90bde6505e43434596ff6398c2c8acb67ced815b","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add SuspenseList to react-is (#20874)

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

Change-Id: If15a8703f19d4a87b7ee5ac5e5b3fc4a5d248b78","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/464dc50569cba1bbf7f3817438dd9abc2a39bf2c"},{"sha":"0047edb7b1d35d588c3e3fb5bfe7de60c67c351c","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Return failure for ops with zero results in TF dialect folding hook

Currently, the hook returns success for ops like tf.Yield that doesn't have any side effect and zero results. That will cause canonicalizer or any other pass using the greedy rewriter to not converge. Canonicalizer pass doesn't handle return value of the greedy rewriter so this change doesn't have any observable effect for canonicalizer.

Added test is passing before this change as well because the canonicalizer pass ignores convergence issue in the rewriter.

Ran into this issue while using greedy rewriter to replace _XlaHostComputeMlir op by XlaHostCompute op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362167274
Change-Id: Iff52406ef046948798dfc4dffd2f183ce32c6f31","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/d2ba4e94da8198b77f667927b4cf21988b3d4d0d"},{"sha":"b503269ae778de3d6d2cbf96e6e5fbe914f37ef8","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /
